ce:section.ce:para:
The preparation of BSQDs was subjected to various microwave powers, including 540, 720, and 900 W, resulting in high QY at 540 and 900 W. After that, the microwave irradiation time was also changed from 2 to 8 min while keeping the other factors fixed. From this study, the QY value increased upon changing irradiation time from 2 to 6 min, while it decreased after 8 min. Additionally, different volumes of water (3, 5, and 7 mL) were attempted. It was noticed that, as the volume of water increased, the QY decreased. With the aid of the QbD approach, the variable factors that influence the quantum yield of the prepared dots could be easily optimized and improved. Depending on the preliminary study, QbD was used to select the effective optimization conditions by studying microwave power (540 and 900 W), irradiation time (2 and 6 min), and water volume (3 and 5 mL). In this study, 23
                        full factorial design was applied as it included two levels and three independent factors (Table 1
                        ).

The factorial design could also provide the main effect, interaction, and optimization plots, confirming the appropriate optimization conditions needed to obtain a high throughput of BSQDs but with a shorter study time, as indicated in Fig. 2

                        (A-C). The Pareto chart (Fig. 2D) illustrates that irradiation time has a greater influence on the QY of the prepared dots than other factors.It was found that, finally, high QY was obtained by using 3 mL of ultra-pure water for 6 min at 900 W (Table 1
                        ). The optimal conditions accomplished throughout the study were then applied. Unlike CQDs produced by other substrates, loading forms, and complex surface functionalization, the precursor of BSQDs has plentiful sources, environmental safety, and a simple preparation method, facilitating large-scale production.

To verify the precision of the developed method, it was used for assaying three samples of increasing concentrations (3.0, 5.0, and 7.0 µg/mL) three times on the same day and on three consecutive days under the optimal detection conditions. Minimal values of %RSD < 2 % indicate the high precision of the designed method (
                           Supplementary Table S3
                        ).
